  "prompt": "Are there specific laws targeting money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are specific laws targeting money laundering in many countries. In the United States, key anti-money laundering (AML) laws include:\n\n1. Bank Secrecy Act (1970)\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandates record-keeping and reporting of cash transactions\n\n2. Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- Criminalized money laundering as a federal crime\n- Established penalties for individuals and organizations\n\n3. USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced AML regulations\n- Increased reporting requirements\n- Strengthened information sharing between financial institutions\n\n4. Corporate Transparency Act (2021)\n- Requires businesses to report beneficial ownership information\n- Aims to prevent financial crimes\n\nInternationally, organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) set global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nMost countries have similar laws designed to:\n- Detect and prevent financial crimes\n- Require transaction monitoring\n- Impose reporting obligations\n- Establish criminal penalties\n- Facilitate international cooperation in investigating financial crimes\n\nThese laws typically apply to banks, financial institutions, casinos, and other businesses dealing with significant financial transactions.",
